[
    {
        "content": "<p>One of my PhD students has formalized a proof of the following statement: if B is a subbasis for a topological space (i.e. the topology is <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=TopologicalSpace.generateFrom#doc\">docs#TopologicalSpace.generateFrom</a> <code>B</code>) then to check that <code>X</code> is compact, it suffices to show that every open cover by elements of <code>B</code> has a finite subcover. Apparently this is called the Alexander Subbasis Theorem (or Lemma). My initial reaction was that this should be straightforward but they showed me the proof that they'd followed and my first instinct was that this proof was making a real meal of it. The proof was by contradiction, you assume X is not compact, you use Zorn to find some kind of extremal cover with no finite subcover and then intersect with B to get an example of a cover by elements of B with no finite subcover.</p>\n<p>I was not immediately convinced that this was the best way to formalize the result and so I tried coming up with a proof of my own and quickly reduced it (unless I made a mistake) to the following statement.</p>\n<p>Let X be a set and let B be a set of subsets of X. Let C be the set of finite intersections of elements of B. If every cover of X by elements of B has a finite subcover, then every cover of X by elements of C has a finite subcover.</p>\n<p>This now just looks like a statement of pure logic and I wanted to try and prove it without AC at all, but then I read that this Alexander subbasis theorem implies Tychonoff's theorem in a fairly straightforward way so any proof must use some form of AC somehow. However I used to think Tychonoff was \"hard\" until I saw the proof using filters which made it look \"easy\".</p>\n<p>Some questions: am I right in that this purely combinatorial statement about covers by B and covers by C above is the content of this Alexander subbasis theorem or did I overlook something? Is the natural Lean proof of this statement about covers going to use Zorn and contradiction, like in the proof that my student showed me? And is there a slicker proof of this Alexander subbasis theorem if we use filters?</p>",
        "id": 516881134,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1746706541
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Is <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=isCompact_open_iff_eq_finite_iUnion_of_isTopologicalBasis#doc\">docs#isCompact_open_iff_eq_finite_iUnion_of_isTopologicalBasis</a> the \"Alexander Subbasis Theorem\"?</p>",
        "id": 516884521,
        "sender_full_name": "Andrew Yang",
        "timestamp": 1746707609
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh it is only a subbasis. Maybe not then.</p>",
        "id": 516884761,
        "sender_full_name": "Andrew Yang",
        "timestamp": 1746707670
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, the content seems to be getting from a basis to a subbasis (that's the combinatorial problem above)</p>",
        "id": 516885687,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1746707956
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The filter proof would be, take an ultrafilter U on X, consider <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><mi>X</mi><mo>∖</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>U</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\{ b \\in B \\vert X \\setminus b \\in U \\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mord\">∣</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∖</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7335em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span></span></span></span> and then show that if it doesn't converge then it would give a cover of X with no finite subcover? That sounds like a bit less work to formalize given what already exists in Mathlib.</p>",
        "id": 516887292,
        "sender_full_name": "Matthew Jasper",
        "timestamp": 1746708410
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>By the way, I think Alexander subbasis theorem only implies Tychnoff with AC and the theorem itself is not enough?</p>",
        "id": 516904844,
        "sender_full_name": "Andrew Yang",
        "timestamp": 1746713210
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(At least the wikipedia reduction uses AC and according to the above Alexander subbasis theorem only needs ultrafilters)</p>",
        "id": 516904996,
        "sender_full_name": "Andrew Yang",
        "timestamp": 1746713255
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"110038\">@Kevin Buzzard</span> , your combinatorial statement looks like it could be proved using König's lemma. (That's just an intuition, not a fact.)</p>",
        "id": 516978853,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1746737670
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Alexander subbasis theorem is equivalent to the ultrafilter lemma, according to <em>Consequences of the Axiom of Choice</em> (Howard &amp; Rubin). For some reason, I can't find full Tychonoff's theorem in the book, only several weakened form of it. But there's a proof <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tychonoff%27s_theorem#Proof_of_the_axiom_of_choice_from_Tychonoff's_theorem\">on Wikipedia</a> that Tychonoff implies AC, and it's probably well known they're equivalent. (The ultrafilter lemma is surely weaker than AC.)<br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/MWMShGhjuoU-IW9fzjfgjLM-/image.png\">image.png</a><br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/daDy5NeptYhQ1_KU-f2mWYBV/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/MWMShGhjuoU-IW9fzjfgjLM-/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"926x631\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/3121/MWMShGhjuoU-IW9fzjfgjLM-/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div><div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/daDy5NeptYhQ1_KU-f2mWYBV/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"877x353\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/3121/daDy5NeptYhQ1_KU-f2mWYBV/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div>",
        "id": 516980791,
        "sender_full_name": "Junyan Xu",
        "timestamp": 1746738459
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes the combinatorial statement seems very elementary if it's true so I was surprised that it was equivalent to even a weak form of AC.</p>",
        "id": 516983646,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1746739711
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This <a href=\"https://www.ams.org/journals/proc/1967-018-01/S0002-9939-1967-0203680-X/\">paper of Wolk</a>  shows that Alexander's subbase theorem is equivalent to Tychonoff for product of finite spaces.</p>",
        "id": 516985509,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1746740586
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The book you quote gives 14J for Tychonoff for product of compact spaces, which is thus equivalent to the boolean prime ideal theorem, while the general Tychonoff theorem is equivalent to the axiom of choice (a <a href=\"https://www.impan.pl/pl/wydawnictwa/czasopisma-i-serie-wydawnicze/fundamenta-mathematicae/all/37/0/93762/the-tychonoff-product-theorem-implies-the-axiom-of-choice\">theorem of Kelley</a> whose proof uses the axiom of choice for products of finite sets, but Kelley has a strong definition of finite set for which the axiom holds!).</p>",
        "id": 516985525,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1746740594
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>To go back to <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"110038\">@Kevin Buzzard</span> 's initial question: I don't know how much does mathlib care about the various strengths of the axiom of choice, but it might be better to formalize a proof that doesn't use a stronger axiom than the BPI. On the other hand, mathlib is formalized in type theory and I don't know whether the various  comparisons of the axiom of choice would be exactly the same here.</p>",
        "id": 516986022,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1746740837
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think if we add LEM and unique choice as axioms and remove choice, type theory should work pretty similarly to ZF ...</p>\n<p>BTW - 14J is Tychonoff for compact Hausdorff spaces. In some conventions compactness includes Hausdorffness, but not in mathlib. Are you using the convention here?</p>",
        "id": 516988362,
        "sender_full_name": "Junyan Xu",
        "timestamp": 1746742044
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>No I was not using the convention. I was surprised to learn that Tychonoff for quasi-compact (aka compact) spaces is strictly stronger than Tychonoff for compact (ak compact Hausdorff) spaces.</p>",
        "id": 517044392,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1746774841
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>Let X be a set and let B be a set of subsets of X. Let C be the set of finite intersections of elements of B. If every cover of X by elements of B has a finite subcover, then every cover of X by elements of C has a finite subcover.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I think you can deduce this from the Alexander subbasis theorem by considering <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi><mo>:</mo><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo><mi>X</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y:=\\{0,1\\}^X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0913em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\"><span class=\"mclose\">}</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8413em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> with the topology with subbasis <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><msub><mi>Y</mi><mi>S</mi></msub><mo>∣</mo><mi>S</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>B</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\{Y_S \\mid S \\in B\\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3283em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.2222em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∣</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7224em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span></span></span></span>, where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>Y</mi><mi>S</mi></msub><mo>:</mo><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mi>y</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>Y</mi><mo>∣</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∀</mi><mi>x</mi><mo mathvariant=\"normal\">∉</mo><mi>S</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y_S := \\{y \\in Y \\mid \\forall x\\notin S, y(x) = 1\\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3283em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.2222em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∣</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∀</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span></span><span class=\"mord vbox\"><span class=\"thinbox\"><span class=\"llap\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"inner\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.0556em;\"></span></span></span><span class=\"fix\"></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span></span></span></span>. (Notice that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><msub><mi>Y</mi><mi>S</mi></msub><mo>∣</mo><mi>S</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\{Y_S \\mid S\\in\\mathcal{S}\\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3283em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.2222em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∣</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7224em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span></span></span></span> covers <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> iff <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{S}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span></span></span></span> covers <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>, and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mo>⋂</mo><mrow><mi>S</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mi>Y</mi><mi>S</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>Y</mi><mrow><mo>⋂</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\bigcap_{S\\in\\mathcal{S}} Y_S=Y_{\\bigcap{\\mathcal{S}}}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0771em;vertical-align:-0.3271em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"position:relative;top:0em;\">⋂</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1786em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.4003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mrel mtight\">∈</span><span class=\"mord mathcal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3271em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3283em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.2222em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0385em;vertical-align:-0.3552em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3448em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5198em;margin-left:-0.2222em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op mtight\" style=\"position:relative;top:0em;\">⋂</span><span class=\"mspace mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.1952em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathcal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3552em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> so <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><msub><mi>Y</mi><mi>S</mi></msub><mo>∣</mo><mi>S</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\{Y_S \\mid S\\in C\\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3283em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.2222em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∣</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7224em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span></span></span></span> is a basis of the topology.) Since you can also deduce Alexander's theorem from this without choice, they are equivalent.</p>\n<p>(Edit: one can see the equivalence more directly, by simply considering the topology generated by B (then C is a basis of the topology).)</p>\n<p>BTW, Gemini recognized that this statement as a key step in the proof of Alexander's theorem, but also made the mistake of thinking Alexander's theorem is equivalent to AC: <a href=\"https://g.co/gemini/share/6d06a4b874f3\">https://g.co/gemini/share/6d06a4b874f3</a></p>\n<p>(Edit: instead of \"a key step\", it's pretty much simply the end result.)</p>",
